.TH "super" "1" "April 2026" ""
.SH NAME
super \- process data with SuperSQL queries
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]super\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]command\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]super\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[B]\-c\f[R] \f[I]query\f[R]]
[\f[I]file\f[R] \&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]super\f[R] executes SuperSQL queries against data in a variety of
formats.
It operates either as a standalone query engine (detached from any
database) or as the entry point to a hierarchy of sub\-commands for
managing SuperDB databases, inspecting query plans, and accessing
developer tooling.
.PP
When invoked without a sub\-command, \f[B]super\f[R] reads input from
one or more \f[I]file\f[R] arguments, from standard input (when
\f[I]file\f[R] is \f[B]\-\f[R]), or from sources referenced within the
query itself (e.g., via a \f[B]from\f[R] operator or SQL \f[B]FROM\f[R]
clause).
If no query is provided, inputs are scanned and serialized to the output
format unchanged, making \f[B]super\f[R] useful as a format converter.
.PP
Input paths may be local file paths, HTTP/HTTPS/S3 URLs, or \f[B]\-\f[R]
for standard input.
When multiple input files are specified they are processed in order as
if concatenated by a single \f[B]from\f[R] clause.
.PP
If no input is specified, the query receives a single \f[B]null\f[R]
value, analogous to SQL\(cqs default input of a single empty row.
This allows \f[B]super\f[R] to be used as a calculator or to generate
standalone results.
.SS Format Detection
\f[B]super\f[R] automatically infers input formats from file extensions
(e.g., \f[CR].json\f[R], \f[CR].parquet\f[R], \f[CR].sup\f[R]).
For standard input or files without a recognized extension,
\f[B]super\f[R] reads and parses a sample of the data to detect the
format.
Use \f[B]\-i\f[R] to override format inference; when \f[B]\-i\f[R] is
specified, all input files must share the same format.
The \f[CR]line\f[R] format cannot be auto\-detected and always requires
\f[B]\-i line\f[R] or an explicit \f[CR](format line)\f[R] option in a
\f[B]from\f[R] operator.
.PP
Parquet and CSUP require seekable input and cannot be read from standard
input.
.SS Output
Output is written to standard output by default, or to the file or
directory specified by \f[B]\-o\f[R].
When writing to a terminal, the default output format is SUP; otherwise
it is BSUP.
These defaults may be overridden with \f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\-s\f[R], or
\f[B]\-S\f[R].
.PP
For schema\-rigid output formats (Arrow, Parquet), all values in the
output must conform to a single schema.
Use the \f[B]fuse\f[R] or \f[B]blend\f[R] operator to unify
heterogeneous types, or use \f[B]\-split\f[R] to write one file per
distinct type.
.SS Error Handling
Fatal errors (e.g., file not found, filesystem full) cause
\f[B]super\f[R] to exit immediately.
Runtime errors produced by the query itself do not halt execution;
instead they appear as first\-class error values interleaved with normal
output.
These can be detected and filtered using the \f[B]is_error\f[R]
function.
.SS Debugging
Use \f[B]\-C\f[R] to compile and display a query in canonical form
without executing it.
This is useful for understanding how shorthand syntax is expanded, for
example how an implied \f[B]where\f[R] or \f[B]put\f[R] operator is
parsed.
The \f[B]debug\f[R] operator can be inserted anywhere in a pipeline to
trace intermediate values to standard error.
